{"title_page": "Metal Mickey", "text_new": "{{About|the 1980s TV show|the Suede song|Metal Mickey (song)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n[[File:Metal Mickey.jpg|thumb|Metal Mickey, a robot character on UK children's television in the 1980s]]\nIt had loads of Fifa points \n'''Metal Mickey''' is a fictional five-foot-tall [[robot]], as well as the name of a [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] television show starring the same character. The robot character was created, controlled and voiced by [[Johnny Edward]].\n\nThe character of Metal Mickey first appeared on British television in the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] children's magazine show ''[[Saturday Banana|The Saturday Banana]],'' produced by [[Southern Television]] in 1978. [[Humphrey Barclay]] saw Mickey on [[Jimmy Savile]]'s '[[Jim'll Fix It]]' television show. Seeing the children chatting in the marketplace with the friendly robot, this led to the creation of the ''Metal Mickey'' television show. Within a month the pilot had been video-taped and shortly after this the series went live with its first six episodes. 41 episodes were made in total, broadcast over three separate series between September 1980 and January 1983. The show attracted viewing figures of around 12 million at its peak.<ref>Jictar rating</ref> [[Micky Dolenz]], formerly of [[The Monkees]] pop group, was brought in to produce and direct the series along with Nic Phillips and David Crossman.\n\n==''Metal Mickey'' television show==\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Metal Mickey\n| image                = Metal Mickey title card.jpg\n| picture_format       = [[4:3]]\n| creator              = \n| starring             = Metal Mickey\n| writer               = [[Colin Bostock-Smith]] \n| channel              = [[ITV (TV network)|ITV Network]]\n| first_aired          = 6 September 1980\n| last_aired =15 January 1983\n| country              = United Kingdom\n| producer             = [[London Weekend Television]]\n}}\nThe television show was created under [[LWT]]'s [[Humphrey Barclay]] who described ''Metal Mickey'' as a show \"with the appeal of ''[[Star Wars]]'', the [[Dalek]]s and ''[[Mork and Mindy]]''\".<ref>[[The Guardian]], ''Situations vacant''; 27 May 1980</ref> It ran from 1980 to 1983.\n\nThe series was set in the home of an ordinary British family, whose youngest child was a science [[boffin]], who had created Metal Mickey to help around the home.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/comedy/guide/articles/m/metalmickey_1299002058.shtml|title=BBC - Comedy Guide - Metal Mickey|date=3 November 2004|accessdate=18 October 2017|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041103005253/http://www.bbc.co.uk/comedy/guide/articles/m/metalmickey_1299002058.shtml|archivedate=3 November 2004|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The family consisted of a mother and father, three children and a grandmother. The show was made by [[London Weekend Television]] and shown on the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] network, with the entire run of 41 episodes being written by comedy writer [[Colin Bostock-Smith]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.com/television/54151/the_den_of_geek_interview_colin_bostocksmith.html |title=The Den of Geek interview: Colin Bostock-Smith |publisher=Den of Geek |date=2008-05-14 |accessdate=2012-09-24}}</ref>\n\nBritish comedy actress [[Irene Handl]] played the grandmother, whom Mickey affectionately called \"my little fruitbat\". He also referred to his inventor as \"Clever Clogs\", his inventor's sister as \"Stringbean\" and their father as \"Bootface\". Handl was never at home with science fiction, either watching it or appearing in it. She famously told BBC presenter [[Noel Edmonds]], when he asked her whether she cried over the death of [[E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial|E.T.]], \"Why should I cry over a bleedin' [[Vacuum cleaner|Hoover]] attachment?\"\n\nMetal Mickey's catchphrase was \"boogie, boogie\", and his favourite treat were Atomic Thunderbusters (which had the appearance of lemon [[bonbon]]s).\n\n===Cast===\n*[[Michael Stainton]] ...  Father\n*Georgina Melville ...  Mother\n*[[Ashley Knight]] ...  Ken\n*Lucinda Bateson ...  Haley\n*[[Lola Young, Baroness Young of Hornsey|Lola Young]] ...  Janey\n*[[Gary Shail]] ...  Steve\n*Metal Mickey ...  Metal Mickey\n*[[Irene Handl]] ...  Granny\n\n===Production credits===\n*Directors: [[Michael Dolenz]], David Crossman, Nic Phillips\n*Producer: Michael Dolenz\n*Writer: Colin Bostock-Smith\n*Designers: Mike Oxley, Rae George, David Catley, James Dillion, Phil Coulter\n*Music: Phil Coulter\n\n===DVD releases===\nThe first two series of ''Metal Mickey'' have been released on DVD. The third series was due to be released in mid-2009.\n\n==Discography==\nMetal Mickey was credited as artist on several record releases, some of them on his own label \"Mickeypops\":<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.45cat.com/artist/metal-mickey|title=Metal Mickey Discography - UK - 45cat|website=www.45cat.com}}</ref>\n*\"[[Lollipop (1958 song)|Lollipop]]\"/\"Eugene\" ([[EMI]], 1979)\n*\"Metal Mickey Magic\"/\"Meet Metal Mickey\" (Mickeypops, 1980)\n*\"Sillycon Chip\"/\"Dubb Vahzun\" (Mickeypops, 1981)\n*\"Do The Funky Robot\"/\"Do The Funky Robot Again\" (Mickeypops, 1982)\n*\"Theme Tune From 'Metal Mickey'\"/\"Fruitbat Rap\" (Hollywood, 1982)\n*\"[[I Want To Hold Your Hand|I Wanna Hold Your Hand]]\"/\"Eugene Machino\" (Hollywood, 1983)\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of fictional robots and androids]]\n*[[Science fiction sitcom]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0163467|Metal Mickey}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081219110716/http://metalmickey.com/ Metal Mickey Official Site]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090322062612/http://www.itv.com/ClassicTVshows/kids/MetalMickey/default.html Metal Mickey \u2014 ITV TV Classics; including the complete first series available to watch online]\n\n[[Category:1980 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1983 British television series endings]]\n[[Category:1980s British children's television series]]\n[[Category:ITV children's television programmes]]\n[[Category:ITV sitcoms]]\n[[Category:Fictional robots]]\n[[Category:London Weekend Television programmes]]\n[[Category:British television programmes featuring puppetry]]\n[[Category:Television series by ITV Studios]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 1978]]\n[[Category:British science fiction television programmes]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the 1980s TV show|the Suede song|Metal Mickey (song)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}\n[[File:Metal Mickey.jpg|thumb|Metal Mickey, a robot character on UK children's television in the 1980s]]\n\n'''Metal Mickey''' is a fictional five-foot-tall [[robot]], as well as the name of a [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] television show starring the same character. The robot character was created, controlled and voiced by [[Johnny Edward]].\n\nThe character of Metal Mickey first appeared on British television in the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] children's magazine show ''[[Saturday Banana|The Saturday Banana]],'' produced by [[Southern Television]] in 1978. [[Humphrey Barclay]] saw Mickey on [[Jimmy Savile]]'s '[[Jim'll Fix It]]' television show. Seeing the children chatting in the marketplace with the friendly robot, this led to the creation of the ''Metal Mickey'' television show. Within a month the pilot had been video-taped and shortly after this the series went live with its first six episodes. 41 episodes were made in total, broadcast over three separate series between September 1980 and January 1983. The show attracted viewing figures of around 12 million at its peak.<ref>Jictar rating</ref> [[Micky Dolenz]], formerly of [[The Monkees]] pop group, was brought in to produce and direct the series along with Nic Phillips and David Crossman.\n\n==''Metal Mickey'' television show==\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Metal Mickey\n| image                = Metal Mickey title card.jpg\n| picture_format       = [[4:3]]\n| creator              = \n| starring             = Metal Mickey\n| writer               = [[Colin Bostock-Smith]] \n| channel              = [[ITV (TV network)|ITV Network]]\n| first_aired          = 6 September 1980\n| last_aired =15 January 1983\n| country              = United Kingdom\n| producer             = [[London Weekend Television]]\n}}\nThe television show was created under [[LWT]]'s [[Humphrey Barclay]] who described ''Metal Mickey'' as a show \"with the appeal of ''[[Star Wars]]'', the [[Dalek]]s and ''[[Mork and Mindy]]''\".<ref>[[The Guardian]], ''Situations vacant''; 27 May 1980</ref> It ran from 1980 to 1983.\n\nThe series was set in the home of an ordinary British family, whose youngest child was a science [[boffin]], who had created Metal Mickey to help around the home.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/comedy/guide/articles/m/metalmickey_1299002058.shtml|title=BBC - Comedy Guide - Metal Mickey|date=3 November 2004|accessdate=18 October 2017|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041103005253/http://www.bbc.co.uk/comedy/guide/articles/m/metalmickey_1299002058.shtml|archivedate=3 November 2004|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The family consisted of a mother and father, three children and a grandmother. The show was made by [[London Weekend Television]] and shown on the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] network, with the entire run of 41 episodes being written by comedy writer [[Colin Bostock-Smith]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.com/television/54151/the_den_of_geek_interview_colin_bostocksmith.html |title=The Den of Geek interview: Colin Bostock-Smith |publisher=Den of Geek |date=2008-05-14 |accessdate=2012-09-24}}</ref>\n\nBritish comedy actress [[Irene Handl]] played the grandmother, whom Mickey affectionately called \"my little fruitbat\". He also referred to his inventor as \"Clever Clogs\", his inventor's sister as \"Stringbean\" and their father as \"Bootface\". Handl was never at home with science fiction, either watching it or appearing in it. She famously told BBC presenter [[Noel Edmonds]], when he asked her whether she cried over the death of [[E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial|E.T.]], \"Why should I cry over a bleedin' [[Vacuum cleaner|Hoover]] attachment?\"\n\nMetal Mickey's catchphrase was \"boogie, boogie\", and his favourite treat were Atomic Thunderbusters (which had the appearance of lemon [[bonbon]]s).\n\n===Cast===\n*[[Michael Stainton]] ...  Father\n*Georgina Melville ...  Mother\n*[[Ashley Knight]] ...  Ken\n*Lucinda Bateson ...  Haley\n*[[Lola Young, Baroness Young of Hornsey|Lola Young]] ...  Janey\n*[[Gary Shail]] ...  Steve\n*Metal Mickey ...  Metal Mickey\n*[[Irene Handl]] ...  Granny\n\n===Production credits===\n*Directors: [[Michael Dolenz]], David Crossman, Nic Phillips\n*Producer: Michael Dolenz\n*Writer: Colin Bostock-Smith\n*Designers: Mike Oxley, Rae George, David Catley, James Dillion, Phil Coulter\n*Music: Phil Coulter\n\n===DVD releases===\nThe first two series of ''Metal Mickey'' have been released on DVD. The third series was due to be released in mid-2009.\n\n==Discography==\nMetal Mickey was credited as artist on several record releases, some of them on his own label \"Mickeypops\":<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.45cat.com/artist/metal-mickey|title=Metal Mickey Discography - UK - 45cat|website=www.45cat.com}}</ref>\n*\"[[Lollipop (1958 song)|Lollipop]]\"/\"Eugene\" ([[EMI]], 1979)\n*\"Metal Mickey Magic\"/\"Meet Metal Mickey\" (Mickeypops, 1980)\n*\"Sillycon Chip\"/\"Dubb Vahzun\" (Mickeypops, 1981)\n*\"Do The Funky Robot\"/\"Do The Funky Robot Again\" (Mickeypops, 1982)\n*\"Theme Tune From 'Metal Mickey'\"/\"Fruitbat Rap\" (Hollywood, 1982)\n*\"[[I Want To Hold Your Hand|I Wanna Hold Your Hand]]\"/\"Eugene Machino\" (Hollywood, 1983)\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of fictional robots and androids]]\n*[[Science fiction sitcom]]\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0163467|Metal Mickey}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081219110716/http://metalmickey.com/ Metal Mickey Official Site]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090322062612/http://www.itv.com/ClassicTVshows/kids/MetalMickey/default.html Metal Mickey \u2014 ITV TV Classics; including the complete first series available to watch online]\n\n[[Category:1980 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1983 British television series endings]]\n[[Category:1980s British children's television series]]\n[[Category:ITV children's television programmes]]\n[[Category:ITV sitcoms]]\n[[Category:Fictional robots]]\n[[Category:London Weekend Television programmes]]\n[[Category:British television programmes featuring puppetry]]\n[[Category:Television series by ITV Studios]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 1978]]\n[[Category:British science fiction television programmes]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n", "name_user": "2a00:23c4:5183:3500:adb8:9c6a:179:9c65", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metal_Mickey"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bosnia and Herzegovina", "text_new": "{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Viral pandemic in Bosnia and Herzegovina}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bosnia and Herzegovina\n| map2            = \n| places          = \n| legend2         = \n| map1            = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in Bosnia and Herzegovina.svg\n| legend1         = {{center|Map of municipalities with {{color|#c80000|confirmed}} coronavirus cases (as of 2 April)}}\n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n| first_case      = [[Banja Luka]]\n| arrival_date    = 5 March 2020 <br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=5|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}} ago)\n| origin          = {{Plainlist|\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Austria|Austria]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Germany|Germany]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|Italy]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Serbia|Serbia]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Switzerland|Switzerland]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Turkey|Turkey]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|USA]]\n}}\n| deaths          = 14\n| recovery_cases  = 19\n| confirmed_cases = 516\n| suspected_cases = undefined\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{Plainlist|\n* [https://covid-19.ba/ Federation B&H]\n* [https://koronavirususrpskoj.com/ Republika Srpska]\n* [http://www.vlada.bdcentral.net/Publication/NewsCategory/page-1-category-103 Br\u010dko District]\n}}\n}}\nThe '''2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bosnia and Herzegovina''' (''Pandemija koronavirusa u Bosni i Hercegovini'' / \u041f\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438ja \u049d\u043e\u0440o\u043da\u0432\u0438pyca y \u0411oc\u043d\u0438 \u0438 Xep\u0446e\u0433o\u0432\u0438\u043d\u0438) is a current event of [[COVID-19|coronavirus disease 2019]] cases caused by [[SARS-CoV-2|severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] virus strain in [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]].\n\nIts first case was confirmed on 5 March 2020 in Banja Luka. The diagnosed was in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|Italy during the 2020 coronavirus pandemic]]. Later the same day, a second case who was the son of the first case.<ref name=\"n1info.1\" /> On 21 March, the first death in the country from coronavirus was announced in a hospital in [[Biha\u0107]]. The patient was an elderly woman who had been hospitalized two days before.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAs of 2 April 2020, in Bosnia and Herzegovina there were 516 confirmed coronavirus cases, of which 267 were in [[Republika Srpska]]<ref name=\"JZU Institut za javno zdravstvo RS\">{{cite web |title=JZU Institut za javno zdravstvo RS |url=https://www.phi.rs.ba/index.php?view=kategorija&id=45 |website=www.phi.rs.ba |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"koronausrpskoj\">{{cite web |title=\u041a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441 \u0443 \u0421\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0458 {{!}} \u0417\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0447\u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430 \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0435 \u0420\u0435\u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0435 \u0421\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u0435 |url=https://koronavirususrpskoj.com/ |website=\u041a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441 \u0443 \u0421\u0440\u043f\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0458}}</ref>, 243 in the [[Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina]],<ref name=\"zzjzfbih.ba\">{{cite web |title=Dnevni izvje\u0161taj za potvr\u0111ene slu\u010dajeve COVID-19 U FBiH |url=https://www.zzjzfbih.ba/dnevni-izvjestaj-za-potvrdene-slucajeve-covid-19-u-fbih/ |website=ZZJZ FBiH |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"covid-19.ba\">{{cite web |title=Covid-19.ba |url=https://covid-19.ba/ |website=covid-19.ba}}</ref> and 6 in [[Br\u010dko District]].<ref name=\"Vlada Br\u010dko distrikta BiH\">{{cite web |title=Vlada Br\u010dko distrikta BiH |url=http://www.vlada.bdcentral.net/Publication/NewsCategory/page-1-category-103 |website=www.vlada.bdcentral.net}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March 2020, the [[Council of Ministers of Bosnia and Herzegovina]] declared a [[state of emergency]] in all of Bosnia and Herzegovina.<ref>{{cite web |title=Saop\u0107enje i audiozapis konferencije za medije nakon 5. vanredne sjednica Vije\u0107a ministara BiH |url=http://www.vijeceministara.gov.ba/saopstenja/sjednice/saopstenja_sa_sjednica/default.aspx?id=32585&langTag=bs-BA |website=www.vijeceministara.gov.ba |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background prior confirmation==\nUp until 25 February 2020, 12 people were under surveillance as suspected cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.klix.ba/vijesti/bih/u-federaciji-bih-trenutno-je-14-osoba-pod-zdravstvenim-nadzorom-zbog-koronavirusa/200225124|title=U Federaciji BiH trenutno je 14 osoba pod zdravstvenim nadzorom zbog koronavirusa|website=Klix.ba|language=bs-BA|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> In [[Sarajevo]], three Chinese tourists who were showing symptoms had negative test results for the [[virus]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://balkaneu.com/several-suspicious-but-not-confirmed-cases-of-coronavirus-in-bih/|title=Several suspicious but not confirmed cases of coronavirus in BiH|date=2020-02-25|website=Independent Balkan News Agency|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 March, a man from [[Tomislavgrad]] was suspected to have brought the virus from Italy, and was sent to [[Mostar]] for a health checkup. His test result was negative.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://avaz.ba/vijesti/bih/552158/muskarac-iz-tomislavgrada-nema-koronavirus|title=Mu\u0161karac iz Tomislavgrada nema koronavirus|website=[[Dnevni avaz]]}}</ref>\n\n==Major events after confirmation==\n{{main|Timeline of the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bosnia and Herzegovina}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Bosnia and Herzegovina medical cases chart}}\n\nOn 5 March 2020, health officials from Republika Srpska confirmed the first case of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] in the country. Later the same day, the second case was confirmed. These cases were a father and son who were thought to have contracted the virus while visiting Italy.<ref name=\"n1info.1\">{{Cite news|url=http://ba.n1info.com/English/NEWS/a414110/Bosnia-confirms-its-first-case-of-Coronavirus.html|title=Bosnia confirms its first case of coronavirus|website=[[N1 (TV channel)|N1 BA]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 March, the fifth case in Bosnia and Herzegovina was confirmed in the town of [[Zenica]], which was the first confirmed case within the [[Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The first case of coronavirus registered in Zenica |url=http://www.fena.ba/article/1139729/the-first-case-of-coronavirus-registered-in-zenica |website=FENA |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March, the 24th case was confirmed in [[Domaljevac-\u0160amac]]. This patient got the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Germany|disease in Germany]], unlike all others that could be traced to Italy.<ref>{{cite web |title=The fourth case of coronavirus infection confirmed in FBiH today |url=http://fena.ba/article/1140956/the-fourth-case-of-coronavirus-infection-confirmed-in-fbih-today |website=FENA |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, the Republika Srpska Ministry of Health announced the first two recoveries, both from Banja Luka.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ba.n1info.com/Vijesti/a416779/Dvije-osobe-u-BiH-izlijecene-od-korona-virusa-i-pustene-kuci.html|title=Dvije osobe u BiH izlije\u010dene od korona virusa i pu\u0161tene ku\u0107i|website=N1 BA|language=bs-Latn-BA|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March, the first cases were confirmed in the capital, [[Sarajevo]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.klix.ba/vijesti/bih/prva-tri-slucaja-koronavirusa-u-sarajevu-zarazene-jos-tri-osobe-u-tesnju-i-gorazdu/200320174|title=Prva tri slu\u010daja koronavirusa u Sarajevu! Zara\u017eene jo\u0161 tri osobe u Te\u0161nju i Gora\u017edu|website=Klix.ba|language=bs-BA|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, the first death in the country from coronavirus was announced in a hospital in Biha\u0107. The patient was an elderly woman who had been hospitalized two days before.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |title=Prva \u017ertva koronavirusa u BiH: U Biha\u0107u preminula starija \u017eena |url=https://www.klix.ba/vijesti/bih/prva-zrtva-koronavirusa-u-bih-u-bihacu-preminula-starija-zena/200321089 |website=Klix.ba |accessdate=21 March 2020 |language=bs-BA}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, the first cases in Br\u010dko District were confirmed. The cases were two people who arrived to Br\u010dko from the [[Caribbean]] via airports in [[France]] and [[Serbia]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Vlada Br\u010dko distrikta BiH |url=http://www.vlada.bdcentral.net/Publication/Read/u-brckom-dvije-osobe-pozitivne-na-korona-virus |website=www.vlada.bdcentral.net |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Cluster related to \"Igman Konjic\" congress ===\n\nA number of cases in the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina are related to one congress held in [[Konjic]] on 11 March 2020, where company \"Igman\" from Konjic marked 70 years of company existence, and where around 200 people were present.<ref>{{cite web |title=Igman Konjic obilje\u017eava 70 godina postojanja |url=https://nap.ba/news/62478 |website=Novinska agencija Patria |accessdate=21 March 2020 |language=bs-Latn-BA |date=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Kompanija \"Igman\": Direktor \u0110ahid Muratbegovi\u0107 i tri osobe su zara\u017eeni koronavirusom |url=https://www.klix.ba/vijesti/kompanija-igman-direktor-djahid-muratbegovic-i-tri-osobe-su-zarazeni-koronavirusom/200319081 |website=Klix.ba |accessdate=21 March 2020 |language=bs-BA}}</ref> Beside confirmed cases of people from Konjic, among those people there were confirmed cases of people from [[Visoko]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Viso\u010danin koji je zara\u017een koronavirusom je konobar s proslave Igmana u Konjicu |url=https://www.klix.ba/vijesti/bih/visocanin-koji-je-zarazen-koronavirusom-je-konobar-s-proslave-igmana-u-konjicu/200323205 |website=Klix.ba |language=bs-BA}}</ref> [[Te\u0161anj]],<ref name=\"faktor.ba\">{{cite web |title=KCUS: Tri pozitivna slu\u010daja na koronavirus u Sarajevu, jedan iz Te\u0161nja i dva iz Gora\u017eda |url=https://faktor.ba/vijest/kcus-tri-pozitivna-slucaja-na-koronavirus-u-sarajevu-jedan-iz-tesnja-i-dva-iz-gorazda/75136 |website=www.faktor.ba |accessdate=21 March 2020 |language=bs-BA}}</ref> [[Gora\u017ede]],<ref name=\"faktor.ba\"/> [[Novi Travnik]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Novi Travnik: Zbog zara\u017eenog korona virusom blokirane zgrade firme BNT TMiH i soliter u centru grada {{!}} druk\u010diji radio 94.7 FM |url=https://drukciji.ba/2020/03/22/novi-travnik-zbog-zarazenog-korona-virusom-blokirane-zgrade-firme-bnz-tmih-i-soliter-u-centru-grada/ |language=hr}}</ref> and Sarajevo.<ref>{{cite web |last1=PORTAL |first1=Oslobo\u0111enje |title=Oslobo\u0111enje - Prva tri slu\u010daja koronavirusa u Sarajevu! Zara\u017eene jo\u0161 tri osobe u Te\u0161nju i Gora\u017edu |url=https://www.oslobodjenje.ba/vijesti/bih/prva-tri-slucaja-koronavirusa-u-sarajevu-zarazene-jos-tri-osobe-u-tesnju-i-gorazdu-541068 |website=www.oslobodjenje.ba |language=bs-ba}}</ref> This case got media attention after it revealed that one person from [[Serbia]] was present at this event, and after he got back to [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Serbia|Serbia he was confirmed positive for coronavirus]].<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0110ahid Muratbegovi\u0107: Prvi slu\u010daj koronavirusa u bh. nogometu |url=https://radiosarajevo.ba/sport/nogomet/prvi-slucaj-koronavirusa-u-bh-nogometu/370845 |website=Radio Sarajevo}}</ref> Since this confirmation on 16 March, all participants have had to go into obilatory self-isolation, and among people present on this event there were Bosnian singer [[Berin Buturovi\u0107]] who was positive for coronavirus,<ref>{{cite web |title=Berin Buturovi\u0107 potvrdio da je zara\u017een i poslao poruku za javnost |url=https://radiosarajevo.ba/magazin/showbiz/berin-buturovic-dobio-sam-rezultate-na-zalost-pozitivan-sam/370857 |website=Radio Sarajevo}}</ref> as well as Bosnian politician [[Fadil Novali\u0107]] who received a negative result.<ref>{{cite web |last1=V |first1=F. |title=Potvr\u0111eno: Novali\u0107 i D\u017eindi\u0107 negativni na COVID-19 |url=https://radiosarajevo.ba/vijesti/bosna-i-hercegovina/potvrdeno-novalic-i-dzindic-negativni-na-covid-19/370751 |website=Radio Sarajevo}}</ref> On 24 March, the first death from this cluster was reported, who was a driver of the director of this company.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0412\u043e\u0437\u0430\u0447 \u0434\u0438\u0440\u0435\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0430 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0435 \"\u0418\u0433\u043c\u0430\u043d\" \u0438\u0437 \u041a\u043e\u045a\u0438\u0446\u0430 \u0434\u0440\u0443\u0433\u0430 \u0436\u0440\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u0432\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0441\u0430 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0443 \u0411\u0438\u0425 |url=https://www.glassrpske.com/cir/novosti/vijesti_dana/vozac-direktora-kompanije-igman-iz-konjica-druga-zrtva-virusa-korona-u-bih/310388 |website=Glas Srpske |language=sr |date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\nThe following depicts the growth of the coronavirus cases in Bosnia and Herzegovina since 5 March 2020 to 2 April 2020.\n\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=line\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n|width=550\n|colors=#FF4500,#87CEEB, #000000\n|showValues=\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|x=5 Mar, 6 Mar, 7 Mar, 8 Mar, 9 Mar, 10 Mar, 11 Mar, 12 Mar, 13 Mar, 14 Mar, 15 Mar, 16 Mar, 17 Mar, 18 Mar, 19 Mar, 20 Mar, 21 Mar, 22 Mar, 23 Mar, 24 Mar, 25 Mar, 26 Mar, 27 Mar, 28 Mar, 29 Mar, 30 Mar, 31 Mar, 1 Apr, 2 Apr\n|yAxisTitle=Cases\n|legend=\