 iz Konjica |url=https://visoko.co.ba/u-visokom-potvrdjen-prvi-slucaj-koronavirusa-povezan-sa-slucajem-iz-konjica/ |website=Visoko.co.ba |language=bs-BA}}</ref> [[Zenica]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Potvr\u0111en prvi slu\u010daj korona virusa u Zenici |url=https://zenicainfo.ba/2020/03/09/potvrdjen-prvi-slucaj-korona-virusa-u-zenici/ |website=zenicainfo.ba |language=bs-BA |date=9 March 2020}}</ref> [[Zavidovi\u0107i]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Nova dva slu\u010daja koronavirusa u BiH: Jedan pacijent iz Zenice, drugi iz Zavidovi\u0107a |url=https://www.klix.ba/vijesti/bih/nova-dva-slucaja-koronavirusa-u-bih-jedan-pacijent-iz-zenice-drugi-iz-zavidovica/200328141 |website=Klix.ba |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=bs-BA}}</ref> [[\u017dep\u010de]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Jo\u0161 13 pozitivnih na koronavirus iz pet gradova u Bosni i Hercegovini |url=https://www.klix.ba/vijesti/bih/jos-13-pozitivnih-na-koronavirus-iz-pet-gradova-u-bosni-i-hercegovini/200330007 |website=Klix.ba |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=bs-BA}}</ref>\n| align=\"right\"| 29\n| align=\"right\"| 0\n| align=\"right\"| 3\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Total\n! align=\"right\"| 225\n! align=\"right\"| 10\n! align=\"right\"| 5\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\"|{{small|''As of 2 April 2020}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Dnevni izvje\u0161taj za potvr\u0111ene slu\u010dajeve COVID-19 U FBiH |url=https://www.zzjzfbih.ba/dnevni-izvjestaj-za-potvrdene-slucajeve-covid-19-u-fbih/ |website=ZZJZ FBiH }}</ref><ref name=\"covid-19.ba\" />\n|}\n\nAs of 2 April 2020, 6 people from [[Br\u010dko District]] have been infected.\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | \n! scope=\"col\" | Cases\n! scope=\"col\" | Deaths\n! scope=\"col\" | Recoveries\n|-\n| align=\"left\" style=\"background:#EAECF0\"| [[Br\u010dko District]]\n| align=\"right\"| 6\n| align=\"right\"| 0\n| align=\"right\"| 0\n| colspan=\"5\"|{{small|''As of 2 April 2020}}<ref name=\"Vlada Br\u010dko distrikta BiH\"/>\n|}\n\n==Measures==\n===Bosnia and Herzegovina===\n\nThe [[Presidency of Bosnia and Herzegovina]] announced Armed Forces' placement of quarantine tents at the country's borders intended for Bosnian citizens returning home. Every Bosnian citizen arriving to the country is obligated to self-quarantine for 14 days starting from the day of arrival.  Tents will be set up on the northern border with [[Croatia]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Dodik: Od ponedeljka vojska izlazi na granicu i postavlja satore za karantin | url= https://faktor.ba/vijest/dodik-od-ponedjeljka-vojska-izlazi-na-granicu-i-postavlja-satore-za-karantin/74164|website=faktor.ba | access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March 2020, Council of Ministers of Bosnia and Herzegovina issued a decision which forbids for foreign nationals entering Bosnia and Herzegovina to enter from areas with intensive transmission of virus coronas, and especially from: Provinces of the PRC (Wuhan), South Korea, Japan, Italy, Iran, France, Romania, Germany, Austria, Spain, Switzerland and Belgium.<ref>{{cite web |title=Vije\u0107e ministara BiH: Zabranjen ulazak strancima iz podru\u010dja sa intenzivnom transmisijom korona virusa |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/ba/balkan/vije%C4%87e-ministara-bih-zabranjen-ulazak-strancima-iz-podru%C4%8Dja-sa-intenzivnom-transmisijom-korona-virusa/1767130 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March 2020, Council of Ministers of Bosnia and Herzegovina issued a decision which bans entrance for all foreigners, and also from 30 March 2020 all borders at [[List of airports in Bosnia and Herzegovina|airports in Bosnia and Herzegovina]] will be closed for passengers, and airplanes could land only to deliver [[cargo]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Vije\u0107e ministara BiH odlu\u010dilo: Privremeno se zatvaraju aerodromi za putnike u Bosni i Hercegovini |url=https://www.klix.ba/vijesti/bih/vijece-ministara-bih-odlucilo-privremeno-se-zatvaraju-aerodromi-za-putnike-u-bosni-i-hercegovini/200324142 |website=Klix.ba |language=bs-BA}}</ref>\n\n===Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina===\n[[File:Triage tent Sarajevo.jpg|thumb|[[Triage]] tent located in Sarajevo during coronavirus pandemic.]]\nOn 11 March, the [[Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina]], had enacted a 2-week shutdown of all schools, high schools and universities in order to contain the spread of the virus,<ref>{{cite web |title=Na dvije sedmice se obustavlja nastava u \u0161kolama i na fakultetima u FBiH |url=https://www.klix.ba/vijesti/bih/na-dvije-sedmice-se-obustavlja-nastava-u-skolama-i-na-fakultetima-u-fbih/200311085 |website=Klix.ba |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=bs-BA}}</ref> which was later prolonged by all cantons.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nastava u Tuzlanskom kantonu \u0107e biti obustavljena do daljnjeg zbog koronavirusa |url=https://www.klix.ba/vijesti/bih/nastava-u-tuzlanskom-kantonu-ce-biti-obustavljena-do-daljnjeg-zbog-koronavirusa/200326239 |website=Klix.ba |language=bs-BA}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina already had acts of profiteering. Fines have already been passed to local pharmacies and stores who used this situation and high demand for anti-bacterial gels/sprays and surgical masks. They lifted the prices as much as 3 times of the usual price.<ref>{{cite web | title= Apoteci u Sarajevu 10000km kazne zbog trostruko visih cijena|url=https://www.nesradio.com/novo/vijesti/novosti/Apoteci-u-Sarajevu-10000-KM-kazne-zbog-trostruko-visih-cijena/10723}}</ref> Federal inspection has given out fines in the sum of 43.500&nbsp;km (~22.000 Euros).<ref>{{cite web| title=BiH: Tr\u017ei\u0161ni inspektori izrekli 16 kazni zbog podizanja cijena|url=https://www.slobodnaevropa.org/a/30488933.html}}</ref>\n[[File:Makeshift hand sanitizers.jpg|thumb|One of many [[hand sanitizer]]s attached to a lamp post in [[Visoko]]]]\nThe Headquarters of Federation of B&H issued on 18 March an order that banned all public gatherings, suspending the operation of all catering facilities for the preparation and sale of food and beverages, restaurants, pizzerias, confectioneries, beauty salons, hookah bars, coffee bars, discos, tea shops, cafes, private dentists.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pro\u010ditajte naredbe: Zabranjuje se rad kafi\u0107a, objekata za masovno okupljanje... |url=http://ba.n1info.com/Vijesti/a417173/Procitajte-naredbe-Zabranjuje-se-rad-kafica-objekata-za-masovno-okupljanje.html |website=N1 BA |accessdate=18 March 2020 |language=bs-Latn-BA}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web |title=Covid-19.ba |url=https://covid-19.ba/dokumenti/civilna_zastita |website=covid-19.ba}}</ref>\n\nSome cities, such as [[Visoko]], installed [[hand sanitizer]]s through the city, in addition to frequent overnight disinfection of streets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.visoko-rtv.ba/jkpvisoko-zavrsena-dezinfekcija-u-gradu-visoko/|title=JKP\"VISOKO\": ZAVR\u0160ENA DEZINFEKCIJA U GRADU VISOKO|last=Redakcija|date=2020-03-19|website=RTV VISOKO|language=bs-BA|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ba.n1info.com/Vijesti/a416511/Visoko-Pocelo-postavljanje-dozatora-na-javnim-povrsinama-za-dezinfekciju-ruku.html|title=Visoko: Po\u010delo postavljanje dozatora na javnim povr\u0161inama za dezinfekciju ruku|website=N1 BA|language=bs-Latn-BA|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nThe civil protection service of Federation of B&H on 20 March 2020 issued an order, which banned the movement of people under the age of 18 and over 65 in the Federation of BiH.<ref>{{cite web |title=Zabrana kretanja osobama mla\u0111im od 18 godina i starijim od 65 u FBiH |url=https://www.slobodnaevropa.org/a/30499978.html |website=Radio Slobodna Evropa |accessdate=21 March 2020 |language=sh}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March 2020, a [[curfew]] was introduced for the entire Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina every day from 18:00 until 05:00, and its implementation started on 22 March 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=Federalni \u0161tab donio naredbu: Od sutra nave\u010der zabrana kretanja od 18 do 5 sati |url=https://www.klix.ba/vijesti/bih/federalni-stab-donio-naredbu-od-sutra-navecer-zabrana-kretanja-od-18-do-5-sati/200321099 |website=Klix.ba |accessdate=21 March 2020 |language=bs-BA}}</ref> On 29 March 2020, time for curfew was changed to 20:00 until 05:00.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n===Republika Srpska===\n[[File:Coronavirus street desinfection in Doboj.jpg|thumb|Coronavirus street disinfection in [[Doboj]].]]\n[[Republika Srpska]] was first to implement measures, beginning from cities of [[Banja Luka]] and [[Doboj]], where business hours were either limited or all business completely forbidden. The Ministry of Health and Social Security ordered the disinfection of all public spaces and property.<ref>{{cite web | title=Ministar zdravlja naredio dezinfekciju svih javnih objekata i povrsina u rs| url=https://www.klix.ba/vijesti/bih/ministar-zdravlja-naredio-dezinfekciju-svih-javnih-objekata-i-povrsina-u-rs-u/200314046|language=sr-SR}}</ref> Student dormitories in the city of Banja Luka were evacuated for immediate disinfection.<ref>{{cite web|title=Iseljavaju se studentski domovi u Banja Luci|url=https://www.nezavisne.com/novosti/drustvo/Iseljavaju-se-studentski-domovi-u-Banjaluci/588914|language=sr-SR}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 March 2020, Republika Srpska had officially enacted a ban on all public gatherings, shut down all schools, and banned entry to all tourists coming from any of the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|COVID-19 infected countries across the world]] in order to contain the spread of the virus within the country.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bosnia bars entry to travelers from coronavirus-hit countries |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-bosnia/bosnias-serb-region-shuts-schools-bans-public-gatherings-over-coronavirus-idUSKBN20X2CA |website=Reuters |accessdate=11 March 2020 |language=en |date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nBetween 12 and 13 March, numerous cities have made decisions to limit the work of grocery stores, restaurants, caf\u00e9s and completely limit the work of gyms and fitness centers. Banja Luka,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/ba/balkan/banjaluka-uvela-vanredne-mjere-zbog-korona-virusa/1763688|title=Banjaluka uvela vanredne mjere zbog korona virusa|accessdate=Mar 18, 2020}}</ref> [[\u010celinac]], [[Prnjavor, Bosnia and Herzegovina|Prnjavor]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tvk3.info/prnjavor-zbog-korona-virusa-skracenje-radnog-vremena-i-zabrana-rada-naredba-stupa-na-snagu-odmah/|title=Prnjavor: Zbog korona virusa skra\u0107enje radnog vremena i zabrana rada; Naredba stupa na snagu odmah (VIDEO)|date=Mar 13, 2020|website=Televizija K3|accessdate=Mar 18, 2020}}</ref> [[Mrkonji\u0107 Grad]] and Doboj<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://doboj.gov.ba/bs/stab-korona/|title=\u0160tab za vanredne situacije: Naredba o regulisanju rada trgovinskih i drugih objekata na teritoriji Grada Doboja|date=Mar 13, 2020|accessdate=Mar 18, 2020}}</ref> are some of the cities that made these restrictions.\n\nOn 15 March, Banja Luka has decided to close all restaurants and caf\u00e9s in the city, with the exception of drugstores, hotels and motels, where drugstores will be working until 22h and hotels will be working until 18h.<ref>{{cite web|title=Banja Luka uvela nove mjere za spre\u010davanje \u0161irenja korona virusa|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/ba/balkan/banjaluka-uvela-nove-mjere-za-spre%C4%8Davanje-%C5%A1irenja-korona-virusa/1767145|language=sr-SR}}</ref>\n\nThe Minister of Health and Social Security, Alen \u0160erani\u0107, reported that 2026 people are under surveillance in Republika Srpska. \u0160erani\u0107 also noted that only citizens arriving from abroad would be allowed the virus testing, and [[quarantine]] will be made mandatory.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u0160erani\u0107:2026 osoba pod nadzorom u RS. Ne dolazite na samovoljno testiranje.|url=http://ba.n1info.com/Vijesti/a416687/Seranic-2.026-osoba-pod-nadzorom-u-RS-ne-dolazite-samovoljno-na-testiranje.html|language=sr-SR}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March 2020, [[curfew]] was introduced in entire Republika Srpska every day from 20:00 until 05:00,<ref>{{cite web |title=Dodik: U RS se od ve\u010deras uvodi policijski sat |url=http://ba.n1info.com/Vijesti/a418241/Dodik-U-RS-se-od-veceras-uvodi-policijski-sat.html |website=N1 BA |accessdate=21 March 2020 |language=bs-Latn-BA}}</ref> and total ban of movement for people older that 65.<ref>{{cite web |title=Vi\u0161kovi\u0107: Ve\u010deras u 20 sati po\u010dinje policijski sat u RS |url=https://bhrt.ba/viskovic-od-danas-zabranjeno-kretanje-za-starije-od-65-godina-a-za-sve-od-20-00-do-5-sati/1117340/ |website=BHRT |language=bs-BA |date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March 2020 the National Assembly declared the state of emergency in Republika Srpska.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bosnian Serb region declares state of emergency over coronavirus |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-bosnia/bosnian-serb-region-declares-state-of-emergency-over-coronavirus-idUSKBN21F0OQ |website=Reuters.com |accessdate=28 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Br\u010dko District ===\n\nThe Government of [[Br\u010dko District]] is regularly adopting measures for control and prevention of coronavirus pandemic and publish them on their official website.<ref>{{cite web |title=Vlada Br\u010dko distrikta BiH |url=http://www.vlada.bdcentral.net/ |website=www.vlada.bdcentral.net |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSince 22 March 2020, it is prohibited in Br\u010dko District to gather and move in public places and open or closed public areas in a group of three or more persons throughout the day, and [[curfew]] was introduced in entire Br\u010dko District every day from 21:00 until 05:00.<ref>{{cite web |title=U Br\u010dkom na javnom mjestu zabranjeno kretanje tri i vi\u0161e osoba u grupi |url=https://www.klix.ba/vijesti/bih/u-brckom-na-javnom-mjestu-zabranjeno-kretanje-tri-i-vise-osoba-u-grupi/200322116 |website=Klix.ba |accessdate=22 March 2020 |language=bs-BA}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Vlada Br\u010dko distrikta BiH |url=http://www.vlada.bdcentral.net/Publication/Read/donesena-naredba-o-policijskom-casu-u-brckom |website=www.vlada.bdcentral.net |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Impact ==\n[[File:Empty shelves in store.jpg|thumb|Empty shelves for flour in one store in [[Sarajevo]] as a result of panic buying.]]\nMembers of the Board of the Tourism and Hospitality Group of the Foreign Trade Chamber of Bosnia and Herzegovina have warned that the situation in tourism as a sector sensitive to global disruptions and the emergence of a new coronavirus strain could lead to the collapse of all entities operating in the tourism and hospitality sector.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kako \u0107e COVID-19 uticati na bh. turizam: Masovni otkazi dolazaka! |url=https://radiosarajevo.ba/vijesti/bosna-i-hercegovina/kako-ce-covid-19-uticati-na-bh-turizam-masovni-otkazi-dolazaka/369923 |website=Radio Sarajevo |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nFrom 21 March, most of the sports activities were canceled across the entire country, including all football matches in all categories.<ref>{{cite web |title=Odgo\u0111ene utakmice BH Telecom Premijer lige i Kupa BiH |url=https://www.nfsbih.ba/vijesti/nogomet-m/bht-premijer-liga/odgodene-utakmice-bh-telecom-premijer-lige-i-kupa-bih/ |website=www.nfsbih.ba |accessdate=21 March 2020 |language=bs-ba}}</ref>\n\n== International aid ==\nThe countries and [[international organization]]s that have sent aid and funds to Bosnia and Herzegovina, to help fight the pandemic:\n\n* {{Flag|EU}} - The EU is considering two ways to assist Bosnia and Herzegovina, including quick support in provision of up to [[Euro|EUR]] 7 million worth of medical equipment and mid-term adjustment and enforcement of EU support in the amount of up to EUR 50 million for the economic development programmes.<ref>{{cite web |title=EU to assist BiH with provision of medical equipment and mitigation of the COVID-19 impact on the economy |url=https://europa.ba/?p=68202 |website=Europa.ba |accessdate=25 March 2020 |date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Serbia}} - Serbia is assisting Republika Srpska in medicines, protective equipment, and vital clinical machines, and also is assisting entire Bosnia and Herzegovina with food including wheat, corn and soybeans.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sastanak sa srpskim \u010dlanom Predsedni\u0161tva Bosne i Hercegovine |url=https://www.predsednik.rs/lat/pres-centar/vesti/sastanak-sa-srpskim-clanom-predsednistva-bosne-i-hercegovine-28779 |website=Predsednik Republike Srbije |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Switzerland}} - On 23 March 2020, Embassy of Switzerland in Bosnia and Herzegovina informed Minister of Security that Switzerland has allocate 200,000 [[USD]] for assistance to Bosnia and Herzegovina.<ref>{{cite web |title=Na videokonferenciji sa ambasadorima i predstavnicima me\u0111unarodnih organizacija i agencija BiH dobila 7.200.000 eura |url=http://www.msb.gov.ba/vijesti/saopstenja/default.aspx?id=18580&langTag=bs-BA |website=www.msb.gov.ba |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|Turkey}} - Turkey sent humanitarian aid on 24 March 2020 that include protective masks, gloves, protective suits and goggles to [[Red Cross Society of Bosnia and Herzegovina]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Stigla pomo\u0107 iz Turske: Solidarnost sa BiH u te\u0161kim vremenima {{!}} Sarajevo.ba |url=https://www.sarajevo.ba/bs/article/7676/stigla-pomoc-iz-turske-solidarnost-sa-bih-u-teskim-vremenima |website=www.sarajevo.ba |language=bs}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|UN}} - [[United Nations Development Programme]] in Bosnia and Herzegovina urgently financed procurement of 50,000 coronavirus test kits.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bosnia will get 50,000 new coronavirus tests, minister says |url=http://ba.n1info.com/English/NEWS/a418117/Bosnia-will-get-50-000-new-coronavirus-tests-minister-says.html |website=N1 BA |language=bs-Latn-BA}}</ref>\n* {{Flag|USA}} - US Government on 23 March 2020 donated medical materials and other important supplies to the [[Armed Forces of Bosnia and Herzegovina]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sarajevo |first1=US Embassy |title=The first batch of humanitarian assistance from the U.S. Government has arrived to assist the citizens of BiH.  Arriving via U.S. military aircraft and donated to the AFBiH were medical materials and other important supplies.pic.twitter.com/P4ePxJaf8i |url=https://twitter.com/USEmbassySJJ/status/1242071446270214144 |website=@USEmbassySJJ |language=en |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> [[United States Agency for International Development|USAID]] is donating [[United States dollar|$]]1.2 million to Bosnia and Herzegovina to help its laboratory systems, activate case-finding & monitoring, support experts, bolster awareness & community engagement and strengthen prevention.<ref>{{cite web |title=@USAID is donating $1.2 million to #BiH to help its laboratory systems, activate case-finding & monitoring, support experts, bolster awareness & community engagement and strengthen prevention.  #COVID19  #Coronavirus #USAinBiH @USAIDGH @USAIDMarkGreen @USAIDBGlick @USEmbassySJJpic.twitter.com/Z4gWRK364Q |url=https://twitter.com/USAIDBIH/status/1244528920512409600 |website=@USAIDBIH |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en |date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://covid-19.ba/ Official website of Government of the Federation of Bosnia and Herzegovina related to coronavirus pandemic]\n* [https://koronavirususrpskoj.com/ Official website of Government of Republika Srpska related to coronavirus pandemic]\n\n{{Portal bar|Medicine|Europe|Bosnia and Herzegovina}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bosnia and Herzegovina| ]]\n[[Category:2020 in Bosnia and Herzegovina|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Health in Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n", "name_user": "Smooth O", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Bosnia_and_Herzegovina"}
{"title_page": "Clarence Denmark", "text_new": "{{BLP sources |date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox gridiron football person\n| name = Clarence Denmark\n| team =  Retired\n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| status = out\n| import = yes\n| college = [[University of Arkansas at Monticello|Arkansas-Monticello]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1985|9|29}}\n| death_date = \n| career_highlights = \n| NFL = DEN094503\n| birth_place = [[Jacksonville, Florida]]\n| death_place = \n| number = \n| position1 = Wide receiver\n| height_ft = 5\n| height_in = 11\n| weight_lb = 185\n| playing_years1 = {{NFL Year|2009|2010}}\n| playing_team1 = [[Jacksonville Jaguars]]*\n| playing_years2 = {{CFL Year|2011|2015}}\n| playing_team2 = [[Winnipeg Blue Bombers]]\n| playing_years3 = {{CFL Year|2016}}*\n| playing_team3 = [[Saskatchewan Roughriders]]\n| playing_years4 = {{CFL Year|2016|2017}}\n| playing_team4 = [[Winnipeg Blue Bombers]]\n| career_footnotes = <nowiki/>*Offseason and/or practice squad member only\n| CFLAllStar = {{CFL Year|2014}}\n| CFLWestAllStar = {{CFL Year|2014}}\n| CFL=clarence-denmark/148563/\n}}\n'''Clarence Traneil Denmark''' (born September 29, 1985) is a former [[Canadian football]] [[wide receiver]]. He most recently played for the [[Winnipeg Blue Bombers]] of the [[Canadian Football League]] (CFL).  Prior to his time in the CFL, Denmark played for the [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] of the [[NFL]]. He played [[college football]] at [[Mississippi Delta Community College]], [[Troy University]], and [[University of Arkansas at Monticello|Arkansas-Monticello]].\n\n==Professional career ==\n\n=== Jacksonville Jaguars ===\nDenmark was signed as an [[undrafted free agent]] by the [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] on August 2, 2009. Denmark, however, was waived on September 1, 2009. He was later signed to the [[practice squad]] on December 5, 2009. Denmark was signed as a free agent on January 5, 2010 and he spent the entire offseason with the team; however he was cut on September 4, 2010. On September 13, 2010, Denmark was signed to the practice squad, but subsequently waived five days later. On November 2, 2010, Denmark was once again added to the Jaguars' practice squad.\n\n=== Winnipeg Blue Bombers ===\nOn May 16, 2011, the Winnipeg Blue Bombers signed Denmark as an import player. Denmark had seven catches for 89 yards and a touchdown in Winnipeg's two pre-season games. Denmark made his first regular season start during Week 2 of the [[2011 CFL season]]: He made four receptions for a total of 38 yards. He would finish his inaugural CFL season as the Bombers second best WR with 818 yards and 5 touchdowns. 2012 was a bit of a down season for Denmark, he only amassed 620 yards and 1 touchdown. He was the leading receiver for the Blue Bombers in both the [[2013 Winnipeg Blue Bombers season|2013]] and [[2014 Winnipeg Blue Bombers season|2014]] seasons. In 2013, he accumulated 900 receiving yards and 4 touchdowns, in 2014, he finished second in the league in receiving yards with 1,080 and added 3 touchdowns. His performance was recognized when he was named not only a CFL West All-Star, but a CFL All-Star. Denmark played in all 18 regular season games in this 5th season with the Bombers, catching 57 passes for 718 yards. He was released by the Blue Bombers on March 22, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bluebombers.com/2016/03/22/bombers-release-turner-denmark/|title=Bombers release Turner & Denmark|website=Winnipeg Blue Bombers|access-date=2016-03-23}}</ref> His career totals with the Bombers are 306 receptions for 4,165 yards with 16 touchdowns. He also added 141 rushing yards on 25 carries, and 14 tackles .\n\n=== Saskatchewan Roughriders ===\nOn May 13, 2016, Denmark signed with the [[Saskatchewan Roughriders]]. On June 19, 2016, he was released as part of the Roughriders final cuts.\n\n=== Second stint with Winnipeg ===\nOn July 31, 2016, Denmark was brought back by the Blue Bombers due to injuries to Winnipeg's regular starting receivers. His first game back with the Blue Bombers was a Week 7 victory over Hamilton, in which he recorded seven catches for 69 yards, including a touchdown.<ref name=\"Tait\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cfl.ca/2016/08/06/euphoric-feeling-denmarks-return-a-special-moment/|title=EUPHORIC FEELING: DENMARK'S RETURN A SPECIAL MOMENT|last=Tait|first=Ed|date=5 August 2016|work=CFL.ca|accessdate=8 August 2016}}</ref> He finished the season with 53 catches for 705 yards and eight touchdowns in just 10 games played. In the following off-season, he entered free agency, but eventually re-signed with the Blue Bombers for a seventh season on February 17, 2017.<ref>[http://www.bluebombers.com/2017/02/17/bombers-agree-terms-denmark/ Bombers agree to terms with Denmark]</ref> He played in all 18 games in 2017, recording 58 catches for 608 receiving yards and seven touchdowns. In the following off-season, he was not offered another contract by the Blue Bombers and became a free agent.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.winnipegfreepress.com/sports/football/bombers/bond-denmark-part-ways-with-bombers-473579763.html |title=Budget squeeze leads Blue to part with Denmark, Bond|date=Feb 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe resides in [[Jacksonville, Florida]]. He attended [[Robert E. Lee High School (Jacksonville, Florida)|Robert E. Lee High School]].\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101125073603/http://jaguars.com/Team/Player.aspx?id=2908 Jacksonville Jaguars Bio]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20141124024639/http://www.bluebombers.com/roster/show/id/3593 Winnipeg Blue Bombers Bio]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Denmark, Clarence}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football wide receivers]]\n[[Category:Canadian football wide receivers]]\n[[Category:American players of Canadian football]]\n[[Category:Arkansas\u2013Monticello Boll Weevils football players]]\n[[Category:Jacksonville Jaguars players]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Florida]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Jacksonville, Florida]]\n[[Category:Troy Trojans football players]]\n[[Category:Winnipeg Blue Bombers players]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources |date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox gridiron football person\n| name = Clarence Denmark\n| team =  Retired\n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| status = out\n| import = yes\n| college = [[University of Arkansas at Monticello|Arkansas-Monticello]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1985|9|29}}\n| death_date = \n| career_highlights = \n| NFL = DEN094503\n| birth_place = [[Jacksonville, Florida]]\n| death_place = \n| number = \n| position1 = Wide receiver\n| height_ft = 5\n| height_in = 11\n| weight_lb = 185\n| playing_years1 = {{NFL Year|2009|2010}}\n| playing_team1 = [[Jacksonville Jaguars]]*\n| playing_years2 = {{CFL Year|2011|2015}}\n| playing_team2 = [[Winnipeg Blue Bombers]]\n| playing_years3 = {{CFL Year|2016}}*\n| playing_team3 = [[Saskatchewan Roughriders]]\n| playing_years4 = {{CFL Year|2016|2017}}\n| playing_team4 = [[Winnipeg Blue Bombers]]\n| career_footnotes = <nowiki/>*Offseason and/or practice squad member only\n| CFLAllStar = {{CFL Year|2014}}\n| CFLWestAllStar = {{CFL Year|2014}}\n| CFL=clarence-denmark/148563/\n}}\n'''Clarence Traneil Denmark''' (born September 29, 1985) is a former[[Canadian football]] [[wide receiver]. He most recently played for the [[Winnipeg Blue Bombers]] of the [[Canadian Football League]] (CFL).  Prior to his time in the CFL, Denmark played for the [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] of the [[NFL]]. He played [[college football]] at [[Mississippi Delta Community College]], [[Troy University]], and [[University of Arkansas at Monticello|Arkansas-Monticello]].\n\n==Professional career ==\n\n=== Jacksonville Jaguars ===\nDenmark was signed as an [[undrafted free agent]] by the [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] on August 2, 2009. Denmark, however, was waived on September 1, 2009. He was later signed to the [[practice squad]] on December 5, 2009. Denmark was signed as a free agent on January 5, 2010 and he spent the entire offseason with the team; however he was cut on September 4, 2010. On September 13, 2010, Denmark was signed to the practice squad, but subsequently waived five days later. On November 2, 2010, Denmark was once again added to the Jaguars' practice squad.\n\n=== Winnipeg Blue Bombers ===\nOn May 16, 2011, the Winnipeg Blue Bombers signed Denmark as an import player. Denmark had seven catches for 89 yards and a touchdown in Winnipeg's two pre-season games. Denmark made his first regular season start during Week 2 of the [[2011 CFL season]]: He made four receptions for a total of 38 yards. He would finish his inaugural CFL season as the Bombers second best WR with 818 yards and 5 touchdowns. 2012 was a bit of a down season for Denmark, he only amassed 620 yards and 1 touchdown. He was the leading receiver for the Blue Bombers in both the [[2013 Winnipeg Blue Bombers season|2013]] and [[2014 Winnipeg Blue Bombers season|2014]] seasons. In 2013, he accumulated 900 receiving yards and 4 touchdowns, in 2014, he finished second in the league in receiving yards with 1,080 and added 3 touchdowns. His performance was recognized when he was named not only a CFL West All-Star, but a CFL All-Star. Denmark played in all 18 regular season games in this 5th season with the Bombers, catching 57 passes for 718 yards. He was released by the Blue Bombers on March 22, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bluebombers.com/2016/03/22/bombers-release-turner-denmark/|title=Bombers release Turner & Denmark|website=Winnipeg Blue Bombers|access-date=2016-03-23}}</ref> His career totals with the Bombers are 306 receptions for 4,165 yards with 16 touchdowns. He also added 141 rushing yards on 25 carries, and 14 tackles .\n\n=== Saskatchewan Roughriders ===\nOn May 13, 2016, Denmark signed with the [[Saskatchewan Roughriders]]. On June 19, 2016, he was released as part of the Roughriders final cuts.\n\n=== Second stint with Winnipeg ===\nOn July 31, 2016, Denmark was brought back by the Blue Bombers due to injuries to Winnipeg's regular starting receivers. His first game back with the Blue Bombers was a Week 7 victory over Hamilton, in which he recorded seven catches for 69 yards, including a touchdown.<ref name=\"Tait\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cfl.ca/2016/08/06/euphoric-feeling-denmarks-return-a-special-moment/|title=EUPHORIC FEELING: DENMARK'S RETURN A SPECIAL MOMENT|last=Tait|first=Ed|date=5 August 2016|work=CFL.ca|accessdate=8 August 2016}}</ref> He finished the season with 53 catches for 705 yards and eight touchdowns in just 10 games played. In the following off-season, he entered free agency, but eventually re-signed with the Blue Bombers for a seventh season on February 17, 2017.<ref>[http://www.bluebombers.com/2017/02/17/bombers-agree-terms-denmark/ Bombers agree to terms with Denmark]</ref> He played in all 18 games in 2017, recording 58 catches for 608 receiving yards and seven touchdowns. In the following off-season, he was not offered another contract by the Blue Bombers and became a free agent.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.winnipegfreepress.com/sports/football/bombers/bond-denmark-part-ways-with-bombers-473579763.html |title=Budget squeeze leads Blue to part with Denmark, Bond|date=Feb 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe resides in [[Jacksonville, Florida]]. He attended [[Robert E. Lee High School (Jacksonville, Florida)|Robert E. Lee High School]].\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101125073603/http://jaguars.com/Team/Player.aspx?id=2908 Jacksonville Jaguars Bio]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20141124024639/http://www.bluebombers.com/roster/show/id/3593 Winnipeg Blue Bombers Bio]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Denmark, Clarence}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football wide receivers]]\n[[Category:Canadian football wide receivers]]\n[[Category:American players of Canadian football]]\n[[Category:Arkansas\u2013Monticello Boll Weevils football players]]\n[[Category:Jacksonville Jaguars players]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Florida]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Jacksonville, Florida]]\n[[Category:Troy Trojans football players]]\n[[Category:Winnipeg Blue Bombers players]]\n", "name_user": "Desb42", "label": "safe", "comment": "balance link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clarence_Denmark"}
{"title_page": "Wake Forest University School of Law", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n| name = Wake Forest University<br/>School of Law\n| image = WFU School of Law logo.png\n| image_size = 220px\n| image_alt = Wake Forest University School of Law\n| motto = ''Pro Humanitate'' ([[Latin]])\n| mottoeng = For Humanity\n| established = 1894\n| type = [[Private university|Private]]\n| head_label = Dean\n| head = Jane Aiken\n| faculty = 92\n| staff = \n| students = 632\n| city = [[Winston-Salem]]\n| state = [[North Carolina]]\n| country = United States\n| free_label = [[USNWR]] Ranking\n| free = 42nd<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/wake-forest-university-03120}}</ref>\n| colors = Black & Old gold<br/>{{color box|#000000}}&nbsp;{{color box|#9E7E38}}\n| website = www.law.wfu.edu\n| logo = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n[[File:Worrell, Wake Forest University.jpg|thumb|Worrell Professional Center (School of Law) at Wake Forest University ]]\nThe '''Wake Forest University School of Law''' is one of the professional graduate schools of [[Wake Forest University]].  Located in [[Winston-Salem]], [[North Carolina]], Wake Forest University School of Law is a private [[American Bar Association]] (ABA) accredited law school and is a member of the [[Association of American Law Schools]] (AALS).  The school was established in 1894.  U.S. News & World Report consistently ranks the school among the Top Tier Law Schools in the nation.  The current dean is Jane Aiken.\n\nWake Forest University School of Law has a faculty of 52 Resident Faculty Members and 40 Extended Faculty Members.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://law.wfu.edu/faculty/profile/ |title=Faculty Profiles &#124; Faculty &#124; Wake Forest School of Law |publisher=Law.wfu.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-11-11}}</ref>\n\nThe school is known for emphasizing small classes, and the entering class in 2014 had 179 students.  The Class entering in 2014 had a 25/75% GPA range of 3.37-3.77 and LSAT range of 157 to 163.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://law.wfu.edu/admissions/facts/ |title=Fast Facts &#124; Admissions & Financial Aid &#124; Wake Forest School of Law |publisher=Law.wfu.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-11-11}}</ref> According to Wake Forest's official ABA-required disclosures, 84.8% of the Class of 2016 obtained full-time, long-term, Bar-required or JD Advantage employment within 10 months after graduation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://career.law.wfu.edu/files/2017/04/EmploymentQuestionnaireSummary2016_FINAL.pdf |title=Employment Statistics}}</ref>  The bar passage rate in North Carolina for the Class of 2016 was 81%.\n\n==Publications==\nThe school has three student-run law journals.  The school's flagship journal is the ''[[Wake Forest Law Review]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lawreview.law.wfu.edu/ |title=Wake Forest Law Review - Home |publisher=wakeforestlawreview.com |date= |accessdate=2013-03-24}}</ref>  The school also publishes two specialized journals, the ''Wake Forest Journal of Law & Policy''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lawpolicyjournal.law.wfu.edu/ |title=Journal of Law & Policy &#124; Wake Forest School of Law |publisher=Lawpolicyjournal.law.wfu.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-11-11}}</ref> and the ''Wake Forest Journal of Business and Intellectual Property Law''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ipjournal.law.wfu.edu/ |title=Journal of Business & Intellectual Property Law &#124; Wake Forest School of Law |publisher=Ipjournal.law.wfu.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-11-11}}</ref>\n\n==Rankings==\nThe Wake Forest University School of Law is ranked 42nd in the 2021 U.S. News and World Report.<ref>https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/wake-forest-university-03120</ref>\n\n==Student organizations==\n* [[Student Bar Association]]\n* [[Phi Alpha Delta]]\n* [[Black Law Students Association]]\n* North Carolina [[Student Bar Association]]\n* [[American Constitution Society]]\n* [[Federalist Society]]\n* [[Christian Legal Society]]\n* [[Moot Court]] Board \n* Trial Bar\n* Transactional Law Competition\n* Public Interest Law Organization\n* ''[[Wake Forest Law Review]]''\n* ''Wake Forest Journal of Law & Policy''\n* Texas Young Lawyer Association National Trial Team\n* AAJ Student Trial Advocacy Competition Trial Team\n* OUTLaw<ref>{{cite web|url=http://outlaw.law.wfu.edu|title=Wake Forest University School of Law|website=outlaw.law.wfu.edu}}</ref>\n\n==Student opportunities==\n* '''Metropolitan [[Externship]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]''' - Students spend approximately 35 hours per week interning in a government agency or non-governmental organization. In addition to this practice component, students attend a weekly class session, which explores issues common to the interns.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dc-externship.law.wfu.edu/ |title=Wake Forest School of Law Program in Washington &#124; Wake Forest School of Law |publisher=Dc-externship.law.wfu.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-11-11}}</ref>\n* '''Summer Study Abroad Programs''' in [[London]], [[Venice]], and [[Vienna]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://studyabroad.law.wfu.edu/ |title=Study Abroad &#124; Wake Forest School of Law |publisher=Studyabroad.law.wfu.edu |date=2012-10-30 |accessdate=2012-11-11}}</ref>\n* '''[[Inns of Court]]'''\n* '''[[Guardian Ad Litem]]'''\n* '''[[Pro bono]] Project'''\n\n==Clinics==\n\nThe law school offers seven [[legal clinics]], or programs that allow students to attain practical legal experience through providing legal services to real clients.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://academics.law.wfu.edu/clinics/ |title=Clinics & Field Work &#124; Academics &#124; Wake Forest School of Law |publisher=Academics.law.wfu.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-11-11}}</ref>\n* '''Appellate Advocacy Clinic''' - Students represent clients in a variety of appellate courts, including the Fourth Circuit and the Seventh Circuit.  Students handle an actual appeal from start to finish, with advice and assistance from their professor, who is counsel of record.  Students also travel to Washington, D.C., to observe arguments at the United States Supreme Court.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://appellate-clinic.law.wfu.edu/ |title=Appellate Advocacy Clinic &#124; Wake Forest School of Law |publisher=Appellate-clinic.law.wfu.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-11-11}}</ref>\n* '''Child Advocacy Clinic''' - Students represent children in custody disputes, domestic violence situations, and in issues involving the public school system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://child-clinic.law.wfu.edu/ |title=Child Advocacy Clinic &#124; Wake Forest School of Law |publisher=Child-clinic.law.wfu.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-11-11}}</ref>\n* '''Community Law and Business Clinic''' - A new program, this clinic provides law and graduate business students with an opportunity to develop skills needed to practice in the increasingly complex legal and regulatory environment they will encounter as professionals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://community-clinic.law.wfu.edu/ |title=Community Law & Business Clinic &#124; Wake Forest School of Law |publisher=Community-clinic.law.wfu.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-11-11}}</ref>\n* '''Elder Law Clinic''' - Students provides free legal assistance to moderate income seniors in a variety of legal matters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elder-clinic.law.wfu.edu/ |title=Elder Law Clinic &#124; Wake Forest School of Law |publisher=Elder-clinic.law.wfu.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-11-11}}</ref>\n* '''Innocence and Justice Clinic''' - This clinic has its origins in the Innocence Project in which Wake Forest students review and investigate claims of innocence to determine whether DNA evidence existed that could exonerate inmates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://innocence-clinic.law.wfu.edu/ |title=Innocence and Justice Clinic &#124; Wake Forest School of Law |publisher=Innocence-clinic.law.wfu.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-11-11}}</ref>\n* '''Civil & Criminal Externship Clinic''' - Formerly referred to as the Litigation Clinic, students have the opportunity to receive real world practice experience by working with local attorneys. During the semester, all students receive civil placements with local firms, in-house counsel offices, and the Office of the United States Attorney for the Middle District of North Carolina. Students also spend half of their semester working in a criminal placement. These placements have included private firms as well as prosecutors' and public defenders' offices.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://litigation-clinic.law.wfu.edu/ |title=Litigation Clinic &#124; Wake Forest School of Law |publisher=Litigation-clinic.law.wfu.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-11-11}}</ref>\n*'''Veterans Legal Clinic''' - Students work with former military services members to upgrade their discharge statuses. The lengthy process involves submitting briefs to the pertinent military discharge review board. \n\n== Employment ==\nAccording to Wake Forest's official ABA-required disclosures, 84.8% of the Class of 2016 obtained full-time, long-term, Bar-required or JD Advantage employment within 10 months after graduation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://about.law.wfu.edu/consumer-information/ |title=Employment Statistics}}</ref> \n{{bar box\n|float= \n|title= ABA Employment Summary for 2016 Graduates<ref>{{cite web|url=http://employmentsummary.abaquestionnaire.org/|title=Employment Summary for 2016 Graduates}}</ref>\n|titlebar=#AAF\n|width=550px\n|left1=Employment Status\n|right1=Percentage\n|caption=Total of 184 Graduates\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|Employed - Bar Passage Required (Full-Time, Long-Term)|green|73.3}}\n{{bar percent|Employed - Bar Passage Required (Part-Time and/or Short-Term)|lime|0.5}}\n{{bar percent|Employed - J.D. Advantage|blue|13.0}}\n{{bar percent|Employed - Professional Position|orange|3.8}}\n{{bar percent|Employed - Non-Professional Position|teal|0.0}}\n{{bar percent|Employed - Undeterminable|brown|0.0}}\n{{bar percent|Pursuing Graduate Degree Full Time|purple|2.1}}\n{{bar percent|Unemployed - Start Date Deferred|blue|4.3}}\n{{bar percent|Unemployed - Not Seeking|sienna|0.0}}\n{{bar percent|Unemployed - Seeking|red|2.7}}\n{{bar percent|Employment Status Unknown|silver|0.0}}\n}}\n\n==Costs==\nThe total cost of attendance (indicating the cost of tuition, fees, and living expenses) at Wake Forest University School of Law for the 2013-2014 academic year is $63,518.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://admissions.law.wfu.edu/apply/costs-aid-scholarships/tuition/ |title=Tuition and Expenses}}</ref> The Law School Transparency estimated debt-financed cost of attendance for three years is $234,471.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lstscorereports.com/schools/wake/costs/2013/ |title=Wake Forest University Profile}}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n*[[Kenneth D. Bell]] (J.D. 1983), Judge of the [[United States District Court for the Western District of North Carolina]]\n*[[Joseph Branch]], Former Chief Justice of the [[North Carolina Supreme Court]]\n*[[Rhoda Billings]] (J.D., 1966), Former Justice of the North Carolina Supreme Court\n*[[William Earl Britt]] (LL.B. 1958), Former federal judge for the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of North Carolina]] \n*[[Sidney S. Eagles Jr.]] (J.D. 1964), Former Justice of the [[North Carolina Court of Appeals]]\n*[[James P. Cain]] (J.D. 1984), Former U.S. Ambassador to [[Denmark]]\n*[[Elizabeth Kay Dillon]] (J.D. 1986), Federal judge for the [[United States District Court for the Western District of Virginia]]\n*[[Robert L. Ehrlich]] (J.D., 1982), Former Governor of and Congressman for the state of [[Maryland]]\n*[[Rocky Fitzsimmons]], member of the [[West Virginia Senate]]\n*[[Jerome B. Friedman]] (J.D., 1969), Federal judge for the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of Virginia]]\n*[[Kay Hagan]] (JD, 1978), Former [[U.S. Senator]] for the state of [[North Carolina]] (2009-2015)\n*[[Johnson Jay Hayes]] (LL.B. 1909), Judge of the [[United States District Court for the Middle District of North Carolina]]\n*[[Malcolm Jones Howard]], (J.D. 1970), Federal judge for the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of North Carolina]] \n*[[Samuel Johnson Howard]] (J.D. 1976), 8th Bishop of the Episcopal Diocese of [[Florida]]\n*[[Woodrow Wilson Jones]] (LL.B. 1937), Federal judge for the [[Western District of North Carolina]]\n*[[Cheslie Kryst]] (J.D. 2017), [[Miss USA]] 2019 and television presenter\n*[[I. Beverly Lake Jr.]] (J.D. 1960), Former Chief Justice of the [[North Carolina Supreme Court]]\n*[[John C. Martin (judge)|John C. Martin]] (J.D. 1967), Chief Judge of the [[North Carolina Court of Appeals]]\n*[[Warren McGraw]] (J.D. 1963), Former Chief Justice of the [[Supreme Court of Appeals of West Virginia]] and West Virginia Senate President\n*[[Robert Burren Morgan]] (J.D.), Former U.S. Senator for the state of North Carolina (1975\u20131981)\n*[[Anuraag Singhal]] (J.D. 1989), Judge of the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of Florida]]\n*[[Emory M. Sneeden]] (LL.B. 1953), Judge of the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit]]\n*[[Edwin Monroe Stanley]] (LL.B., 1931), Former federal judge for the [[United States District Court for the Middle District of North Carolina]] \n*[[Charles H. Taylor]] (J.D., 1966) Former U.S. Representative for the state of North Carolina (1991\u20132007)\n*[[Norwood Tilley]] (J.D. 1969), Federal judge for the [[United States District Court for the Middle District of North Carolina]]\n*[[Don Vaughan (North Carolina politician)|Don Vaughan]] (J.D., 1979) Former member of the [[North Carolina State Senate]] from [[Greensboro, North Carolina|Greensboro]]\n*[[Hiram Hamilton Ward]] (LL.B., 1950) Former federal judge for the [[United States District Court for the Middle District of North Carolina]]\n*[[Samuel Grayson Wilson]] (J.D. 1974) Federal Judge for the [[United States District Court for the Western District of Virginia]]\n*[[Christopher R. Barron]] (J.D.), Co-Founder of [[GOProud]].\n*[[Greg Habeeb]] (J.D., 2001) Member of the [[Virginia House of Delegates]].\n*[[Creigh Deeds]] (J.D., 1984) Member of the [[Virginia State Senate]].\n*[[Suzanne Reynolds]] (J.D., 1977) Dean Emerita and Professor of Law at Wake Forest School of Law.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://law.wfu.edu}}\n\n{{Law Schools of the Southeast}}\n{{coord|36.1372|-80.2748|region:US-NC_type:edu|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wake Forest University School Of Law}}\n[[Category:Law schools in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Wake Forest University]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n| name = Wake Forest University<br/>School of Law\n| image = WFU School of Law logo.png\n| image_size = 220px\n| image_alt = Wake Forest University School of Law\n| motto = ''Pro Humanitate'' ([[Latin]])\n| mottoeng = For Humanity\n| established = 1894\n| type = [[Private university|Private]]\n| head_label = Dean\n| head = Jane Aiken\n| faculty = 92\n| staff = \n| students = 632\n| city = [[Winston-Salem]]\n| state = [[North Carolina]]\n| country = United States\n| free_label = [[USNWR]] Ranking\n| free = 42nd<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/wake-forest-university-03120}}</ref>\n| colors = Black & Old gold<br/>{{color box|#000000}}&nbsp;{{color box|#9E7E38}}\n| website = www.law.wfu.edu\n| logo = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n[[File:Worrell, Wake Forest University.jpg|thumb|Worrell Professional Center (School of Law) at Wake Forest University ]]\nThe '''Wake Forest University School of Law''' is one of the professional graduate schools of [[Wake Forest University]].  Located in [[Winston-Salem]], [[North Carolina]], Wake Forest University School of Law is a private [[American Bar Association]] (ABA) accredited law school and is a member of the [[Association of American Law Schools]] (AALS).  The school was established in 1894.  U.S. News & World Report consistently ranks the school among the Top Tier Law Schools in the nation.  The current dean is Jane Aiken.\n\nWake Forest University School of Law has a faculty of 52 Resident Faculty Members and 40 Extended Faculty Members.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://law.wfu.edu/faculty/profile/ |title=Faculty Profiles &#124; Faculty &#124; Wake Forest School of Law |publisher=Law.wfu.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-11-11}}</ref>\n\nThe school is known for emphasizing small classes, and the entering class in 2014 had 179 students.  The Class entering in 2014 had a 25/75% GPA range of 3.37-3.77 and LSAT range of 157 to 163.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://law.wfu.edu/admissions/facts/ |title=Fast Facts &#124; Admissions & Financial Aid &#124; Wake Forest School of Law |publisher=Law.wfu.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-11-11}}</ref> According to Wake Forest's official ABA-required disclosures, 84.8% of the Class of 2016 obtained full-time, long-term, Bar-required or JD Advantage employment within 10 months after graduation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://career.law.wfu.edu/files/2017/04/EmploymentQuestionnaireSummary2016_FINAL.pdf |title=Employment Statistics}}</ref>  The bar passage rate in North Carolina for the Class of 2016 was 81%.\n\n==Publications==\nThe school has three student-run law journals.  The school's flagship journal is the ''[[Wake Forest Law Review]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lawreview.law.wfu.edu/ |title=Wake Forest Law Review - Home |publisher=wakeforestlawreview.com |date= |accessdate=2013-03-24}}</ref>  The school also publishes two specialized journals, the ''Wake Forest Journal of Law & Policy''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lawpolicyjournal.law.wfu.edu/ |title=Journal of Law & Policy &#124; Wake Forest School of Law |publisher=Lawpolicyjournal.law.wfu.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-11-11}}</ref> and the ''Wake Forest Journal of Business and Intellectual Property Law''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ipjournal.law.wfu.edu/ |title=Journal of Business & Intellectual Property Law &#124; Wake Forest School of Law |publisher=Ipjournal.law.wfu.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-11-11}}</ref>\n\n==Rankings==\nThe Wake Forest University School of Law was ranked 32nd in the 2018 U.S. News & World Report Best Law Schools rankings,<ref>[http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/law-rankings/page+2 U.S. News & World Report Best Law Schools], 2018</ref> and 31st in the 2019 rankings.<ref>https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-law-schools/wake-forest-university-03120</ref>\n\n==Student organizations==\n* [[Student Bar Association]]\n* [[Phi Alpha Delta]]\n* [[Black Law Students Association]]\n* North Carolina [[Student Bar Association]]\n* [[American Constitution Society]]\n* [[Federalist Society]]\n* [[Christian Legal Society]]\n* [[Moot Court]] Board \n* Trial Bar\n* Transactional Law Competition\n* Public Interest Law Organization\n* ''[[Wake Forest Law Review]]''\n* ''Wake Forest Journal of Law & Policy''\n* Texas Young Lawyer Association National Trial Team\n* AAJ Student Trial Advocacy Competition Trial Team\n* OUTLaw<ref>{{cite web|url=http://outlaw.law.wfu.edu|title=Wake Forest University School of Law|website=outlaw.law.wfu.edu}}</ref>\n\n==Student opportunities==\n* '''Metropolitan [[Externship]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]''' - Students spend approximately 35 hours per week interning in a government agency or non-governmental organization. In addition to this practice component, students attend a weekly class session, which explores issues common to the interns.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dc-externship.law.wfu.edu/ |title=Wake Forest School of Law Program in Washington &#124; Wake Forest School of Law |publisher=Dc-externship.law.wfu.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-11-11}}</ref>\n* '''Summer Study Abroad Programs''' in [[London]], [[Venice]], and [[Vienna]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://studyabroad.law.wfu.edu/ |title=Study Abroad &#124; Wake Forest School of Law |publisher=Studyabroad.law.wfu.edu |date=2012-10-30 |accessdate=2012-11-11}}</ref>\n* '''[[Inns of Court]]'''\n* '''[[Guardian Ad Litem]]'''\n* '''[[Pro bono]] Project'''\n\n==Clinics==\n\nThe law school offers seven [[legal clinics]], or programs that allow students to attain practical legal experience through providing legal services to real clients.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://academics.law.wfu.edu/clinics/ |title=Clinics & Field Work &#124; Academics &#124; Wake Forest School of Law |publisher=Academics.law.wfu.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-11-11}}</ref>\n* '''Appellate Advocacy Clinic''' - Students represent clients in a variety of appellate courts, including the Fourth Circuit and the Seventh Circuit.  Students handle an actual appeal from start to finish, with advice and assistance from their professor, who is counsel of record.  Students also travel to Washington, D.C., to observe arguments at the United States Supreme Court.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://appellate-clinic.law.wfu.edu/ |title=Appellate Advocacy Clinic &#124; Wake Forest School of Law |publisher=Appellate-clinic.law.wfu.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-11-11}}</ref>\n* '''Child Advocacy Clinic''' - Students represent children in custody disputes, domestic violence situations, and in issues involving the public school system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://child-clinic.law.wfu.edu/ |title=Child Advocacy Clinic &#124; Wake Forest School of Law |publisher=Child-clinic.law.wfu.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-11-11}}</ref>\n* '''Community Law and Business Clinic''' - A new program, this clinic provides law and graduate business students with an opportunity to develop skills needed to practice in the increasingly complex legal and regulatory environment they will encounter as professionals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://community-clinic.law.wfu.edu/ |title=Community Law & Business Clinic &#124; Wake Forest School of Law |publisher=Community-clinic.law.wfu.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-11-11}}</ref>\n* '''Elder Law Clinic''' - Students provides free legal assistance to moderate income seniors in a variety of legal matters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elder-clinic.law.wfu.edu/ |title=Elder Law Clinic &#124; Wake Forest School of Law |publisher=Elder-clinic.law.wfu.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-11-11}}</ref>\n* '''Innocence and Justice Clinic''' - This clinic has its origins in the Innocence Project in which Wake Forest students review and investigate claims of innocence to determine whether DNA evidence existed that could exonerate inmates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://innocence-clinic.law.wfu.edu/ |title=Innocence and Justice Clinic &#124; Wake Forest School of Law |publisher=Innocence-clinic.law.wfu.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-11-11}}</ref>\n* '''Civil & Criminal Externship Clinic''' - Formerly referred to as the Litigation Clinic, students have the opportunity to receive real world practice experience by working with local attorneys. During the semester, all students receive civil placements with local firms, in-house counsel offices, and the Office of the United States Attorney for the Middle District of North Carolina. Students also spend half of their semester working in a criminal placement. These placements have included private firms as well as prosecutors' and public defenders' offices.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://litigation-clinic.law.wfu.edu/ |title=Litigation Clinic &#124; Wake Forest School of Law |publisher=Litigation-clinic.law.wfu.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-11-11}}</ref>\n*'''Veterans Legal Clinic''' - Students work with former military services members to upgrade their discharge statuses. The lengthy process involves submitting briefs to the pertinent military discharge review board. \n\n== Employment ==\nAccording to Wake Forest's official ABA-required disclosures, 84.8% of the Class of 2016 obtained full-time, long-term, Bar-required or JD Advantage employment within 10 months after graduation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://about.law.wfu.edu/consumer-information/ |title=Employment Statistics}}</ref> \n{{bar box\n|float= \n|title= ABA Employment Summary for 2016 Graduates<ref>{{cite web|url=http://employmentsummary.abaquestionnaire.org/|title=Employment Summary for 2016 Graduates}}</ref>\n|titlebar=#AAF\n|width=550px\n|left1=Employment Status\n|right1=Percentage\n|caption=Total of 184 Graduates\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|Employed - Bar Passage Required (Full-Time, Long-Term)|green|73.3}}\n{{bar percent|Employed - Bar Passage Required (Part-Time and/or Short-Term)|lime|0.5}}\n{{bar percent|Employed - J.D. Advantage|blue|13.0}}\n{{bar percent|Employed - Professional Position|orange|3.8}}\n{{bar percent|Employed - Non-Professional Position|teal|0.0}}\n{{bar percent|Employed - Undeterminable|brown|0.0}}\n{{bar percent|Pursuing Graduate Degree Full Time|purple|2.1}}\n{{bar percent|Unemployed - Start Date Deferred|blue|4.3}}\n{{bar percent|Unemployed - Not Seeking|sienna|0.0}}\n{{bar percent|Unemployed - Seeking|red|2.7}}\n{{bar percent|Employment Status Unknown|silver|0.0}}\n}}\n\n==Costs==\nThe total cost of attendance (indicating the cost of tuition, fees, and living expenses) at Wake Forest University School of Law for the 2013-2014 academic year is $63,518.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://admissions.law.wfu.edu/apply/costs-aid-scholarships/tuition/ |title=Tuition and Expenses}}</ref> The Law School Transparency estimated debt-financed cost of attendance for three years is $234,471.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lstscorereports.com/schools/wake/costs/2013/ |title=Wake Forest University Profile}}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n*[[Kenneth D. Bell]] (J.D. 1983), Judge of the [[United States District Court for the Western District of North Carolina]]\n*[[Joseph Branch]], Former Chief Justice of the [[North Carolina Supreme Court]]\n*[[Rhoda Billings]] (J.D., 1966), Former Justice of the North Carolina Supreme Court\n*[[William Earl Britt]] (LL.B. 1958), Former federal judge for the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of North Carolina]] \n*[[Sidney S. Eagles Jr.]] (J.D. 1964), Former Justice of the [[North Carolina Court of Appeals]]\n*[[James P. Cain]] (J.D. 1984), Former U.S. Ambassador to [[Denmark]